Peel the @ginger{1%thumb} with a #spoon{}, then mince or grate along with the @garlic{2%cloves}. Remove the tough ribs and stems from the @kale{4%ounce}, then thinly slice. Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Finely chop the @chili pepper{1}, removing seeds if you don't like a lot of heat.

Heat @olive oil{1%teaspoon} in a #pot{} over medium heat. Add the onion and cook ~{2%minutes}, until slightly softened.

Add the garlic, ginger, and 1/4 teaspoon chopped Thai chili (or more if you like the heat!) to the pot, and cook ~{30%seconds}, until fragrant.

Add the @ground pork{10%ounce} and cook, breaking up pieces, ~{6-8%minutes}, until no longer pink. Season with @salt{1%tsp} and @pepper{1%tsp}.

Add @water{4%cups} and the @pho stock concentrate{2} to the pot. Stir to combine, then add the kale and @soy sauce{2%tablespoon} to the pot. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a simmer for ~{5%minutes}.

Once the kale has slightly softened, add the @udon noodles{4%ounce}. Cook ~{5%minutes}, until al dente. Taste and season with salt and pepper as necessary.

Serve the soup in #bowls{} and enjoy! If you have chopsticks, now is the time to use them!

> Be sure to wash your hands, knife, and cutting board with dish soap after preparing the Thai chili. The oil-dissolving properties will remove any traces of spiciness that can irritate your eyes and skin.